5:T5f9,
      <p>White ink is the most expensive component of DTF printing, and it's also the most difficult to manage. <strong>CADlink Digital Factory 11</strong> addresses these challenges head-on with its revolutionary <strong>Single-Pass Highlight White</strong> technology.</p>

      <h3>What is Single-Pass Highlight White?</h3>
      <p>Traditional RIP software lays down a solid layer of white ink under every pixel of color. Digital Factory 11 is smarter. It analyzes the image and applies a variable amount of white ink depending on the opacity needed. In areas where high brightness is required (highlights), it boosts the white ink. In darker areas, it reduces it.</p>

      <h3>The Benefits</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cost Savings:</strong> Users report saving up to 20-30% on white ink consumption.</li>
        <li><strong>Softer Hand Feel:</strong> Less ink means a thinner, more flexible print that moves with the fabric.</li>
        <li><strong>Faster Drying:</strong> Thinner ink layers cure faster and more evenly in the oven.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Automated Underbase Generation</h3>
      <p>Forget about manually creating spot channels in Photoshop. Digital Factory 11 automatically generates the white underbase on the fly, supporting transparent PNGs, TIFFs, and even vector files perfectly.</p>

      <p>If you're looking to improve your print quality while cutting costs, upgrading your RIP software to handle white ink intelligently is the single most effective step you can take.</p>
